00:02:52.580 --> 00:02:55.070
controller, sort of.

00:02:55.070 --> 00:02:57.370
As you can see, I've already
been experimenting with one of

00:02:57.370 --> 00:02:59.860
the samples, before I dove into
creating my own project,

00:02:59.860 --> 00:03:00.910
which everyone should do.

00:03:00.910 --> 00:03:03.430
Because experimenting is good,
and you'll find out what you

00:03:03.430 --> 00:03:04.270
don't know.

00:03:04.270 --> 00:03:07.260
But we're going to
add a new game.

00:03:07.260 --> 00:03:10.180
Then, we get to set up the
services for our app, which

00:03:10.180 --> 00:03:13.160
doesn't use Google's APIs
yet, which makes sense.

00:03:13.160 --> 00:03:14.160
A lot of people aren't yet.

00:03:14.160 --> 00:03:15.340
But they should.

00:03:15.340 --> 00:03:20.770
And then we add the "Angry
Fruit" Package Name.

00:03:20.770 --> 00:03:25.360
So going on from there, we end
up getting this fabulous

00:03:25.360 --> 00:03:27.960
dialogue telling us about
branding information, which

00:03:27.960 --> 00:03:30.580
I'm not going to cover.

00:03:30.580 --> 00:03:32.920
But other people will cover
these things in another talk.

00:03:32.920 --> 00:03:40.070
And then finally, after all
of this, there we are.

00:03:40.070 --> 00:03:41.320
We now get to the fun part.

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:45.760
So what we've done now is, we've
actually extracted from

00:03:45.760 --> 00:03:50.940
that APK file the SHA1
Certificate Fingerprint that

00:03:50.940 --> 00:03:52.830
you're going to be using
for that client.

00:03:52.830 --> 00:03:59.080
And this actually is creating
a client on Google's Apiary

00:03:59.080 --> 00:04:01.070
dashboard, which is the way
these things are all designed.

00:04:01.070 --> 00:04:04.700
The code.google.com dashboard,
that's an internal name.

00:04:04.700 --> 00:04:09.410
And note that we end up getting
this lovely the screen

00:04:09.410 --> 00:04:14.030
here, which contains this very
large client ID and this 12

00:04:14.030 --> 00:04:16.300
digit number, which is
the application ID.

00:04:16.300 --> 00:04:21.050
And this is what we actually
put into the package, so

00:04:21.050 --> 00:04:23.030
again, not that whole thing.

00:04:23.030 --> 00:04:26.100
So finally, we end up getting
into some code.

00:04:26.100 --> 00:04:29.420
And very simply, this is
our manifest file.

00:04:29.420 --> 00:04:33.990
And that is the little section
there that contains the App ID

00:04:33.990 --> 00:04:35.260
that we're sending to
these services.

00:04:35.260 --> 00:04:37.160
Now, notice that we
actually have two

00:04:37.160 --> 00:04:38.340
separate services here.

00:04:38.340 --> 00:04:39.680
One of them is for App State.

00:04:39.680 --> 00:04:41.130
And the other one
is for Games.

00:04:41.130 --> 00:04:44.070
And the reason why is, App State
obviously has a lot of

00:04:44.070 --> 00:04:47.710
applications beyond games.

00:04:47.710 --> 00:04:50.030
And that is the App ID that
we're going to place in.

00:04:50.030 --> 00:04:52.690
Now, notice that it
is a resource.

00:04:52.690 --> 00:04:56.760
And the reason we're doing that
is, because otherwise,

00:04:56.760 --> 00:04:58.430
the Android Resource System
will actually

00:04:58.430 --> 00:05:00.070
interpret it as a number.

00:05:00.070 --> 00:05:01.760
We want it to be a string.

00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:04.140
So don't just put it in
the manifest file.

00:05:04.140 --> 00:05:06.980
And then, here we are.

00:05:06.980 --> 00:05:07.780
There's our App ID.

00:05:07.780 --> 00:05:10.120
And we put it inside
of our resources.

00:05:10.120 --> 00:05:15.230
So very simply, now we set up
our program for launch.

00:05:15.230 --> 00:05:18.550
Except there's one problem here,
because we have a game

00:05:18.550 --> 00:05:20.930
that'll work with the Play
Services API, signed with our

00:05:20.930 --> 00:05:22.020
release keys, which
is what we're

00:05:22.020 --> 00:05:23.280
going to actually publish.

00:05:23.280 --> 00:05:26.650
However, no one actually
develops an Android game,

00:05:26.650 --> 00:05:27.870
using the release keys.

00:05:27.870 --> 00:05:29.760
Or if you are, you really
shouldn't, because you should

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:30.850
protect that key store.

00:05:30.850 --> 00:05:32.260
That is your identity,
your digital

00:05:32.260 --> 00:05:33.810
identity on Google Play.

00:05:33.810 --> 00:05:36.660
So how do we make it work
with the Debug Key?

00:05:36.660 --> 00:05:40.260
Well, that's very simply we
go and link another app.

00:05:40.260 --> 00:05:42.670
And the other app has the same
package name as our regular

00:05:42.670 --> 00:05:44.040
application.

00:05:44.040 --> 00:05:48.630
And we end up getting a blank
value for the SHA1 Because we

00:05:48.630 --> 00:05:51.310
didn't actually upload
that APK.

00:05:51.310 --> 00:05:54.400
So where do we get
this value from?

00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:55.550
Well, it depends on
what platform

00:05:55.550 --> 00:05:57.290
you're actually running.

00:05:57.290 --> 00:06:02.180
We create this automatically for
you on Linux, Windows, or

00:06:02.180 --> 00:06:04.170
Vista Plus, or whatever.

00:06:04.170 --> 00:06:08.010
The important thing is that, you
should probably take and

00:06:08.010 --> 00:06:10.180
actually go through the step
of sharing the same Debug

00:06:10.180 --> 00:06:11.960
Keystore across your developers,
because we only

00:06:11.960 --> 00:06:14.400
allow you to create a limited
number of client

00:06:14.400 --> 00:06:16.220
IDs for your game.

00:06:16.220 --> 00:06:19.360
So it's a good practice
to be, in any case.

00:06:19.360 --> 00:06:24.530
And then, after all of this,
we actually get the SHA

00:06:24.530 --> 00:06:27.520
fingerprint by using Keytool.

00:06:27.520 --> 00:06:30.510
So now we can take that
fingerprint, dump it back into

00:06:30.510 --> 00:06:31.560
this new client.

00:06:31.560 --> 00:06:34.250
And now we are ready.

00:06:34.250 --> 00:06:36.760
And all of our developers will
actually be able to develop

00:06:36.760 --> 00:06:39.500
against Play Services.

00:06:39.500 --> 00:06:40.740
Now we're in a good place.

00:06:40.740 --> 00:06:45.880
But what about actually
integrating the Games APIs?

00:06:45.880 --> 00:06:47.886
Jenny, what's the deal
with branding?

00:06:47.886 --> 00:06:50.450
JENNIE LEES: So we've come up
with some guidelines to help

00:06:50.450 --> 00:06:52.760
you integrate the Games Services
and make a really

00:06:52.760 --> 00:06:55.470
consistent experience
for your players.

00:06:55.470 --> 00:06:57.740
First of all, two very
important notes--

00:06:57.740 --> 00:07:00.070
to be a Games Services
customer, you

00:07:00.070 --> 00:07:01.670
need to do two things.

00:07:01.670 --> 00:07:03.630
First of all, you need
to use Sign-In.

00:07:03.630 --> 00:07:05.870
And then, because signing in
without any features is

00:07:05.870 --> 00:07:08.280
useless, you also need
to have achievements.

00:07:08.280 --> 00:07:11.280
So let's start by looking
at Sign-In.

00:07:11.280 --> 00:07:14.910
Because we use Google+ for our
sign in and our identity, so

00:07:14.910 --> 00:07:16.950
should you, for the branding.

00:07:16.950 --> 00:07:20.020
We have a very small, red
g+ logo you can use.

00:07:20.020 --> 00:07:22.420
Or if you want something bigger,
there's a full version

00:07:22.420 --> 00:07:24.110
with Sign-In.

00:07:24.110 --> 00:07:27.200
In a game context though, if you
just stick that red button

00:07:27.200 --> 00:07:29.600
somewhere, with no explanation,
no context, it's

00:07:29.600 --> 00:07:30.910
kind of confusing.

00:07:30.910 --> 00:07:33.960
Why would I ever tap that,
if I'm a player?

00:07:33.960 --> 00:07:39.090
So we want you to really give an
upsell, explain what you're

00:07:39.090 --> 00:07:41.800
using it for, what you're
going to do with it, why

00:07:41.800 --> 00:07:43.255
should the player bother?

00:07:43.255 --> 00:07:45.180
There are all these great
features that are waiting to

00:07:45.180 --> 00:07:46.740
be unlocked when they sign in.

00:07:46.740 --> 00:07:48.850
So let them understand that.

00:07:48.850 --> 00:07:50.740
And this is from "Save the
Puppies." They did a great job

00:07:50.740 --> 00:07:52.880
in just making it
really clear.

00:07:52.880 --> 00:07:54.360
You want to collect
achievements.

00:07:54.360 --> 00:07:55.890
You want to compete
with your friends.

00:07:55.890 --> 00:07:58.150
Come right in.

00:07:58.150 --> 00:08:01.617
For the end game features
themselves, we have icons to

00:08:01.617 --> 00:08:05.660
fit each of them, that you can
use and customize, in texture

00:08:05.660 --> 00:08:06.990
and your game's look and feel.

00:08:06.990 --> 00:08:09.780
You don't have to use them
as these flat vectors.

00:08:09.780 --> 00:08:12.090
And we do provide our own
interface for leaderboards and

00:08:12.090 --> 00:08:13.090
achievements.

00:08:13.090 --> 00:08:16.500
Now, we ask that you put in a
way to get to that interface.

00:08:16.500 --> 00:08:19.320
And we really thoroughly
encourage you to mess about

00:08:19.320 --> 00:08:23.300
with our data APIs and customize
skin, use the data

00:08:23.300 --> 00:08:26.100
in your own games UI,
as much as you like.

00:08:26.100 --> 00:08:29.010
If you want to put a little
button to bring up our UI, you

00:08:29.010 --> 00:08:31.450
should use our branding to make
it really clear to the

00:08:31.450 --> 00:08:34.190
player what's going to happen
and make it a really

00:08:34.190 --> 00:08:36.549
consistent experience.

00:08:36.549 --> 00:08:38.970
The controller is the main
symbol for this.

00:08:38.970 --> 00:08:40.850
And as you'll see in the games
that are live on the Play

00:08:40.850 --> 00:08:44.100
Store today, the controller is
used a lot to say, this is

00:08:44.100 --> 00:08:45.430
where the games services are.

00:08:45.430 --> 00:08:47.370
This is where the cool
stuff lives.

00:08:47.370 --> 00:08:50.140
And if you have a page, like a
menu, which has achievements

00:08:50.140 --> 00:08:52.790
and leaderboards and maybe even
multiplayer, you don't

00:08:52.790 --> 00:08:53.990
want to put like three
controllers.

00:08:53.990 --> 00:08:55.840
That means absolutely nothing.

00:08:55.840 --> 00:08:59.330
So you can use the controller
as like a contextual key and

00:08:59.330 --> 00:09:02.115
the individual feature
icons for the links.

00:09:02.115 --> 00:09:04.690
Let's look at that
in practice.

00:09:04.690 --> 00:09:09.270
So you can see, as with the
HandyGames screen shot we have

00:09:09.270 --> 00:09:12.140
on the bottom there, they've
used the controller as like

00:09:12.140 --> 00:09:12.900
tying things in.

00:09:12.900 --> 00:09:14.900
And they've used individual
icons, with completely their

00:09:14.900 --> 00:09:17.420
own look and feel there,
to launch our UIs.

00:09:17.420 --> 00:09:19.190
You have to be boring.

00:09:19.190 --> 00:09:23.490
Just keep one really simple
principle in mind.

00:09:23.490 --> 00:09:25.550
We don't want people
to be confused,

00:09:25.550 --> 00:09:29.060
surprised, upset, or angry.

00:09:29.060 --> 00:09:30.400
Angry?

00:09:30.400 --> 00:09:34.160
I would be angry, if I played
a game for hours.

00:09:34.160 --> 00:09:36.110
And right at the end of all
that play, I'm told, hey,

00:09:36.110 --> 00:09:37.820
maybe you could sign
in, through some

00:09:37.820 --> 00:09:39.450
obscure menu somewhere.

00:09:39.450 --> 00:09:41.570
And none of that progress
gets synced.

00:09:41.570 --> 00:09:44.240
None of that counted, because
I wasn't signed in.

00:09:44.240 --> 00:09:50.040
So keep people nice and give
them a reason to use the

00:09:50.040 --> 00:09:57.147
services and not get angry at
you, because that's bad.

